Problem Description

Design an algorithm to encode a list of strings into a single string and then decode it back to the original list of strings.

Your implementation should provide two methods:

encode(List<String> strs)
Takes a list of strings and converts it into a single encoded string.
decode(String s)
Takes the encoded string and reconstructs the original list of strings.

The encoding and decoding should be lossless, meaning:

decode(encode(strs)) == strs

for any valid input.

Notes
The strings may contain any characters, including:
Letters
Digits
Spaces
Special characters
Empty strings ("")
You cannot rely on a delimiter like ',' or '#' alone because those characters may also appear inside the strings.
There is no restriction on the contents of the strings, so your encoding scheme must uniquely identify the boundaries of each string.


We need to store the size of the string -> when encoding.
but we need to careful because the string maycontain -> numbers and delimeters..


The standard solution

Use the length of the string.
Encode each string as:
length + '#' + string

Example:

["cat", "hello"]
becomes
3#cat5#hello



During decoding:

Read digits until #.
Convert them to an integer len.
Read the next len characters—they belong to the string.
Repeat.





class Codec {
public:

    // Encodes a list of strings to a single string.
    string encode(vector<string>& strs) {

        string encoded = "";

        for (string &str : strs) {

            encoded += to_string(str.size());
            encoded += '#';
            encoded += str;
        }

        return encoded;
    }

    // Decodes a single string to a list of strings.
    vector<string> decode(string s) {

        vector<string> result;

        int i = 0;

        while (i < s.size()) {

            // Read the length
            int j = i;

            while (s[j] != '#')
                j++;

            int len = stoi(s.substr(i, j - i));

            // Move past '#'
            j++;

            // Read the next 'len' characters
            result.push_back(s.substr(j, len));

            // Move to the next encoded string
            i = j + len;
        }

        return result;
    }
};
